=== Fractal Rhythms and Irrational Proportions<sec:fractal-rhythms>

==== Introduction

The preceding sections of this chapter have examined rhythmic subdivisions through two complementary lenses. The taxonomy presented in @sec:taxonomy organised the space of subdivision patterns along four structural axes — tuplet size, absolute size, groove balance, and potential energy — drawing on the classification developed in Huguenin 2014. The study of Quplets and Huplets in @sec:quplets then examined a more analytic question: how two concurrent subdivisions of sizes $n$ and $d$ interact dynamically, producing continuous families of crest trajectories whose endpoints are canonically anchored Euclidean rhythms. Both sections share an assumption worth making explicit: the rhythmic object under study occupies a single level of organisation. Whether classified, compared, or continuously deformed, each pattern is treated as a subdivision of one pulse cycle — a single stratum of the rhythmic hierarchy.

This sub-chapter turns to a different object. I consider here what happens when the mechanism that produces a subdivision is _iterated_ upon its own output: when a pattern of longs and shorts, obtained by applying a swing rule to a pulse, is itself treated as a string of symbols to which the same rule can be applied a second time, and then a third, and so on indefinitely. The resulting objects — sequences whose structure reproduces itself at every scale of observation — are what I term _fractal rhythms_.

This shift of viewpoint is not merely quantitative. A single-level subdivision is an object in a simplex; a fractal rhythm is an infinite sequence whose local structure determines, and is determined by, its global structure. The mathematical tools required differ accordingly. Where the study of Quplets draws on continuous dynamics in finite-dimensional simplices, the study of fractal rhythms draws on the combinatorics of infinite words and on the theory of
substitution morphisms and their fixed points — a body of mathematics whose application to music theory has been developed over the past two decades, principally through the work on Sturmian words and well-formed scales (Noll 2008; Clampitt & Noll 2018; Allouche & Johnson 2018), and to which the present sub-chapter contributes a rhythmic extension.

The thesis defended in this sub-chapter is twofold. First, fractal rhythms constitute a well-defined class of rhythmic objects. They are generated by substitution rules acting on finite alphabets of durations (typically two letters: $L$ and $S$; or three: $S$, $M$, $L$), and their asymptotic structure is governed by the fixed points of those rules under iteration. Three such fixed points will be shown to arise from three distinct structural constraints: $sqrt(2)$ from the requirement that a binary rule preserve mirror consistency; $phi.alt$, the golden ratio, from the requirement that a binary rule preserve entropy at every level; and $rho$, the plastic number, from the corresponding requirement applied to a ternary rule. Each of these three irrational numbers encodes a specific structural property of the rhythmic object it generates, and the three together form a hierarchy of attractors in the space of infinite subdivisions.

Second, and more fundamentally, the mechanism that generates fractal rhythms is the same mechanism examined in the chapter on properties of swing. The application of unequal durations to a subdivision — what we have called _swing_ — appears in two regimes: a _pointwise_ regime, in which the rule is applied once and the resulting long–short pattern characterises a single pulse cycle; and a _recursive_ regime, in which the rule is applied to its own output and the resulting pattern characterises every scale of the rhythmic object simultaneously. Local swing and fractal rhythms are not two distinct phenomena connected by analogy: they are the same phenomenon observed at different levels of iteration. Among other things, this observation brings the _mirror effect_ of the preceding chapter — a local property of paired subdivisions — into direct relation with the global structure of fractal rhythms: the mirror effect, reframed as a substitution rule, is the first and simplest of the fractal constructions examined below.

The sub-chapter proceeds in four stages. The first reviews the state of research on self-similarity and substitution in music, situating the present contribution within several interconnected bodies of literature: the fractal music tradition initiated by Mandelbrot and consolidated mathematically by Brothers; the compositional precedent of Nørgård's infinity series and its mathematical analysis; the combinatorics of words on finite alphabets and its application to rhythm and scale theory; and the computational generation of multilevel rhythms. The second stage develops the substitution framework in its simplest form: it reframes the mirror effect of the preceding chapter as a substitution rule, and examines the failure mode — the progressive clustering of longs and shorts under straightforward iteration — that motivates the central construction. The third stage presents the three substitution rules and their fixed points in succession, in each case establishing the connection to a well-studied mathematical object (the Fibonacci word, a second Sturmian morphism, the Padovan sequence) and deriving the musical consequences. The fourth stage provides a definition of fractal rhythm as an object, examines the properties that follow from that definition, and closes by situating the resulting construction within the topological perspective that organises the present chapter.

A word on the status of the musical examples used throughout. The substitution rules examined here produce patterns that bear recognisable resemblance to rhythmic figures found in several musical traditions — binary long-short patterns characteristic of jazz phrasing, ternary $S$–$M$–$L$ patterns audible in certain Afro-Brazilian and Afro-Cuban grooves. I will occasionally invoke such resemblances as illustration, and I will use terms such as "samba pattern" as convenient shorthand for specific ternary configurations whose surface structure matches a rhythmic figure heard in that repertoire. These invocations are not claims about the traditions themselves, nor about the provenance of the mathematical structures involved. The mathematical argument stands on its own, and the resemblances to particular traditions are observations to be treated with the same caution as any cross-cultural comparison: the present work is a theoretical essay in rhythm, not an ethnomusicological account.#footnote[A general caveat regarding culturally situated examples is stated in the chapter on swing properties and applies equally here: the use of tradition-derived labels in this thesis is descriptive and schematic, never exhaustive or authoritative.]


==== State of Research <sec:state-of-research>

The study of rhythms generated by substitution and the study of self-similar structures in music draw on several distinct but interconnected bodies of literature. The present sub-chapter contributes to a space populated by music-theoretical, compositional, mathematical, and computational lines of inquiry, each with its own vocabulary and its own priorities. I organise this review around four such lines: the long tradition of fractal analyses of existing music, initiated in the work of Cowell and Stockhausen and consolidated mathematically by Brothers; the compositional precedent set by Nørgård's infinity series and subsequent self-similar techniques; the application of the combinatorics of words to scale and rhythm theory, developed over the past two decades principally within the theory of Sturmian words; and the computational generation of multilevel rhythmic structures, in which the substitution framework has begun to appear as a generative principle. Each of these lines intersects the present work at specific points, and each is situated below in relation to the contribution this sub-chapter aims to make.

#heading(level: 6, numbering: none, outlined: true)[Pitch-rhythm continuity and the fractal tradition]

The observation that rhythm and pitch belong to a single physical continuum, discussed in the first chapter of this Book, has a long prehistory that is directly relevant to the present discussion. Cowell (1930), writing in 1919, proposed that the overtone series could be applied to rhythm as it is to pitch, generating temporal relationships of 2:1, 3:2, 3:4, and so on in exact parallel with harmonic intervals. Stockhausen (1957/1959) extended this observation into a theory of *unified time structuring*, identifying around 16 Hz the approximate threshold at which the auditory system shifts from a rhythmic to a pitched percept. Both authors recognised that the physical continuity between rhythm and pitch must entail some corresponding continuity of structural principles. Neither, however, addressed the recursive dimension that is central to fractal construction: both remained at the level of relating a given rhythmic configuration to a harmonic configuration, without examining what happens when the relating operation is applied to its own output. The treatment of rhythm–pitch continuity in the previous chapter took these authors as starting points while departing from their projects; the present sub-chapter extends this departure by introducing recursion as a structural operation in its own right.

The idea that musical structures can exhibit self-similarity across multiple scales gained significant traction after Mandelbrot's formalisation of fractal geometry in the 1970s. Brothers (2007), at Mandelbrot's suggestion, undertook the first systematic mathematical treatment of fractal music, proposing a rigorous definition: a musical structure is fractal when at least one of its measurable properties exhibits self-similarity governed by a power law. Brothers distinguishes several dimensions along which self-similarity can operate — *duration scaling*, *structural scaling*, *intervallic scaling*, *motivic scaling* — and applies this framework to the analysis of existing compositions, most notably Bach's *Cello Suite No. 3* (Brothers 2007). A subsequent systematic treatment by McDonough & Herczyński (2022) distinguishes two principal types of fractal patterns in music: *prolation canons*, in which several voices simultaneously render the same motif at different tempi, and *nested sequences*, in which finer time scales appear sequentially, each iteration containing all earlier versions. Henderson-Sellers & Cooper, cited by both Brothers and by McDonough & Herczyński, proposed a definition of musical self-similarity based on note durations, explicitly analogous to the Cantor set construction.

These frameworks are powerful analytical tools for examining existing compositions. Their orientation, however, is primarily retrospective: they extract fractal properties from pieces that were not necessarily composed with such properties in mind. The present sub-chapter differs from this tradition in focus. It does not ask whether a given musical piece exhibits fractal properties; it asks what class of rhythmic objects emerges when specific generative rules — rules motivated by musical constraints rather than chosen arbitrarily — are iterated to their fixed points. The object of study is the rhythmic structure itself, not a corpus of compositions, and the argument proceeds by dérivation structurelle rather than by analyse statistique.

#heading(level: 6, numbering: none, outlined: true)[Compositional precedents: Nørgård, Johnson, and motivic scaling]

Before Mandelbrot coined the term *fractal*, the Danish composer Per Nørgård had already developed a compositional technique based on an infinite self-similar integer sequence. Nørgård's *infinity series*, introduced in 1959 and applied systematically in his Symphony No. 2 (1970) and Symphony No. 3 (1972–75), generates pitch sequences whose structure reproduces itself at multiple time scales within a single work (Nørgård, as documented in the IRCAM biographical resource; see also Kullberg 2014). The mathematical properties of the infinity series have been subsequently analysed in rigorous detail by Shallit (2005, 2017), the latter paper appearing in the *Journal of Mathematics and Music*. Shallit establishes the automaticity of the sequence, characterises the note pairs that appear in it, and proves various self-similarity properties, grounding Nørgård's intuition in a formal setting.

Other composers have developed self-similar compositional techniques along different lines. Tom Johnson's *Narayana's Cows* (1989) uses a variant of the Fibonacci sequence introduced by the fourteenth-century Indian mathematician Narayana, generating melodic material through a delayed morphism (Allouche & Johnson 1995). Conlon Nancarrow's studies for player piano exploit prolation canons with precisely controlled tempo ratios. Works by Martin Bresnick, Arvo Pärt, and György Ligeti have been cited as incorporating forms of motivic scaling (Brothers 2007; McDonough & Herczyński 2022).

These compositional precedents share a common trait: each works with a generative rule that is *given* — chosen by the composer for its musical or mathematical appeal — rather than *derived* from a structural constraint internal to the rhythmic phenomenon itself. Nørgård's infinity series is a remarkable structure, but Nørgård did not arrive at it by imposing a condition on what a rhythmic sequence must preserve under iteration; he arrived at it through compositional experimentation. The contribution of the present sub-chapter runs in the opposite direction: it begins with musical constraints (preservation of entropy under iteration, consistency of the mirror relation), derives the substitution rules that satisfy them, and identifies the fixed points that result. The rules are thus not freely chosen but motivated.

#heading(level: 6, numbering: none, outlined: true)[Combinatorics of words and rhythm]

The mathematical framework within which the present sub-chapter operates is the combinatorics of words on finite alphabets, and specifically the theory of *substitution morphisms* and their fixed points. This field has developed a rich body of results concerning infinite sequences generated by iterating a replacement rule, of which the *Fibonacci word* — the infinite sequence $0100101001001 dots$ obtained by iterating the morphism $0 arrow.r 01$, $1 arrow.r 0$ — is the canonical example (Wikipedia s.v. *Fibonacci word*; OEIS A003849). The Fibonacci word is an instance of a broader class known as *Sturmian words*, infinite binary sequences characterised by having exactly $n+1$ distinct factors of length $n$. Sturmian words are uniformly recurrent, balanced, and associated with irrational slopes; their structure is governed by *Sturmian morphisms*, which form a well-studied monoid (Berstel 2007; Berthé, de Luca, & Reutenauer 2008).

The application of this framework to music theory has been developed principally through the *Micrologus* group — Carey, Clampitt, Noll, Amiot — and consolidated in several publications over the past two decades. Carey & Clampitt (1996) first suggested the relevance of Sturmian structures to rhythm; Noll (2008) developed a systematic music-theoretical application of Sturmian sequences and morphisms, focusing primarily on scale theory. Clampitt & Noll (2018) extended the framework to *pairwise well-formed* scales, represented as words over a three-letter alphabet. Boenn (2018) applied *Christoffel words* — the finite analogues of Sturmian words — to rhythmic analysis and composition. A historical survey of the field is available in Allouche & Johnson (2018), published in the *Journal of Mathematics and Music*. Beyond the musicological applications, Adam Rentsch's thesis (La Trobe University) explicitly treats *Sturmian rhythms* as the infinite, non-periodic analogues of Euclidean rhythms.

One further application deserves mention: Marohnić & Strmečki (2012) have proposed that the plastic number $rho$ may be used to construct a chromatic-scale temperament, by defining *Padovan intervals* as a geometric progression on the pitch axis. Their approach, developed within the architectural theory of van der Laan, is extrapolative — generalising a theory of three-dimensional perception to the one-dimensional pitch axis — and does not involve substitution morphisms. It stands as an isolated proposal in a largely unexplored territory: the application of the plastic number to music. The present sub-chapter occupies an adjacent but distinct position, applying $rho$ to the rhythmic domain through a ternary substitution rule rather than to the pitch domain through a perceptual analogy.

Two features of the existing combinatorial literature are worth noting in preparation for what follows. First, it is almost exclusively oriented toward the theory of scales — pitch structures — rather than toward rhythm proper. Noll's (2008) seminal paper opens with *« music-theoretical central instances of such a word: the infinite Pythagorean word »*, and its entire development concerns modes and their transformations. The rhythmic dimension, when it appears, is treated as a straightforward reinterpretation of the scalar framework: binary words become rhythmic patterns by mapping letters to onsets, without further structural adaptation. Second, the connection between the substitution framework and the phenomenon of swing — the microtiming phenomenon examined in the preceding chapter — is entirely absent. Sturmian words and their morphisms have been used to generate rhythmic patterns, but the question of what swing does to subdivisions, whether one-off or iterated, has not been addressed within this framework.

#heading(level: 6, numbering: none, outlined: true)[Algorithmic and computational rhythm generation]

A fourth body of work is relevant to the present discussion: the computational generation of rhythmic structures according to mathematical principles. Toussaint's (2005) foundational paper on *Euclidean rhythms* showed that a wide class of traditional rhythmic patterns can be described as the output of Euclid's algorithm applied to two integers: the number of onsets and the number of pulse subdivisions. The Euclidean framework has since been extended in several directions, notably to include well-formed rhythms, nested hierarchies, and morphing between configurations. Milne, Bulger, Herff, Sethares, and Dean have developed this line substantively, proposing the mathematical concepts of *perfect balance* (Milne, Bulger, Herff, Sethares 2015; Milne, Bulger, Herff 2017) and implementing the software *XronoMorph* for the generation of multilevel balanced and well-formed rhythms (Milne, Herff, Bulger, Sethares, Dean 2016; Milne & Dean 2016). The relationship between the present work and that of Milne and colleagues raises broader questions of positioning that are addressed elsewhere in this thesis; here it suffices to note that their framework is oriented toward balance as a geometric property (the centroid of onsets at the circle centre) rather than toward substitution as a generative mechanism, and that swing as microtiming is not a parameter in their system.

#heading(level: 6, numbering: none, outlined: true)[Positioning the present contribution]

The state of research sketched above leaves a specific gap open. The fractal tradition provides frameworks for analysing self-similarity in existing compositions, but offers no generative principles motivated by musical constraints. The compositional precedents of Nørgård and others introduce self-similar structures but treat their generative rules as given rather than derived. The combinatorial tradition supplies the mathematical tools — substitution morphisms, fixed points, Sturmian words — but has applied them primarily to scales rather than to rhythms, and has not connected them to the microtiming phenomenon of swing. The computational tradition generates rhythmic structures algorithmically, but through criteria of balance and evenness rather than through recursive substitution.

The present sub-chapter contributes to this space at three specific points. First, it proposes substitution rules motivated by musical constraints — entropy preservation under iteration, consistency of the mirror relation — and derives the fixed points that these constraints imply, rather than choosing the rules a priori. Second, it connects the resulting framework to the microtiming phenomenon of swing examined in the preceding chapter, showing that local swing and recursive fractality are two regimes of a single mechanism. Third, it applies the substitution framework to the rhythmic domain proper, bringing its results into contact with a body of musical practice — the traditional grooves of Afro-Brazilian, Afro-Cuban, and West African provenance that employ ternary $S$–$M$–$L$ subdivisions — whose theoretical treatment has so far remained outside the combinatorial literature. None of these contributions is wholly independent of the prior work on which it builds, but their combination constitutes, I hope, a coherent extension of the existing frameworks into territory those frameworks have not yet addressed.

